comments.body:
[~spark], couldn't you do the same thing with passing userdata powershell script when you launch a Windows instance?  I guess I am wondering whats the difference between injecting a powershell script using sshd versus injecting a powershell script using userdata?  If we want to update the Windows Integration Tool on a running instance, can't we use something like [this|http://blogs.technet.com/b/heyscriptingguy/archive/2006/06/21/how-can-i-use-windows-powershell-to-start-a-service-on-a-remote-computer.aspx]?

[~mclark], thanks for listing down the testing lifecycle.  Questions inline:

{code}
2)Direct remote interaction with the guest
{code}

When you say "direct", what do you mean (i.e. RDP driven or something that will test RDP)?   I found a few links here that may help:

* http://gallery.technet.microsoft.com/scriptcenter/Connect-Mstsc-Open-RDP-2064b10b
* http://blogs.technet.com/b/heyscriptingguy/archive/2006/06/21/how-can-i-use-windows-powershell-to-start-a-service-on-a-remote-computer.aspx

{code}
3)Runs on a Linux server
{code}

Trying to understand this a bit more.  Whats the reliance on running on a Linux server?  For logging?  For job control?  Just curious, could we use the [Jenkins Copy-To-Slave plugin|https://wiki.jenkins-ci.org/display/JENKINS/Copy+To+Slave+Plugin] to kick off jobs or is that too much?  Here is another link that I found that may be helpful:

* http://www.krenger.ch/blog/wmi-commands-from-linux/

{code}
4) Debug-able through logs after execution of a test. If the test has to be re-run or run outside of the automated env in order to debug, than we lose most of our benefit. 
{code}

Would [centralized logging from Windows to Linux|http://www.rsyslog.com/using-rsyslog-windows-agent-as-a-syslog-relay/] work here?  I know one of the features from EUCA-5553, to write event log entries to the console to help with troubleshooting, but I didn't know if this would work (i.e. run euca-get-console-output and redirect it to a file)?

{code}
5)Ideally this remote access method would exist and be usable w/o any Eucalyptus software to allow us to test any software created by Eucalyptus, ...outside Eucalyptus.
{code}

So I take it if we had a way to integrate access with eutester, this would be best (just a clarification question)?  

Thanks again for the conversation guys.   Look forward to hearing from you guys soon.

[~spark], understood.  This is why I shared the links above.  Your statement here:

{code}
The QA guys want to interrogate the VMs directly and it requires SSHD running on windows VM
{code}

Why can't you use a [python script to communicate to a Windows VM from a Linux machine|http://www.krenger.ch/blog/wmi-commands-from-linux/]?  With this, you don't need to install SSHD.  You just use WMI (thats native to Windows).   Does this make sense or am I missing something?  Have we tested this out and it doesn't work and/or meet the requirement?   Just curious, have we tested out Cygwin with SSHD running on a Windows image?  Just wondered if the interaction once you ssh'd into the Windows machine was similar to what you would see on a Linux machine (I did this a long time ago, and I am not sure if the behavior changed or not)?
